restrictions, pressures, and concessions, AP’s Berlin “newshawks” provided more than a thousand U.S. newspapers with extensive coverage of the Nazi campaigns to conquer Europe and annihilate the continent’s Jews.Newshawks in Berlin reveals how the Associated Press covered Nazi Germany from its earliest days through the aftermath of World War II. Larry Heinzerling and Randy Herschaft accessed previously classified government documents; plumbed diary entries, letters, and memos; and reviewed thousands of published stories and photos to examine what the AP reported and what it left out. Their research uncovers fierce internal debates about how to report in a dictatorship, and it reveals decisions that sometimes prioritized business ambitions over journalistic ethics. The book also documents the AP’s coverage of the Holocaust and its unveiling. Featuring comprehensive research and a memorable cast of characters, this book illuminates how the dilemmas of reporting on Nazi Germany remain familiar for journalists reporting on authoritarian regimes today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aForeign correspondentszGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPress coveragezUnited States. 0aNational socialismxPress coverage. 0aPress and politicszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPress and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aCooper, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerschaft, Randy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/hein2101840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231558310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231558310/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles